{"award_age":54.0,"bio_image":"full\/8637c88fcda652ec278736658602213c4a790639.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1896-02-28T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1965-03-30T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/thumb\/a\/a9\/Philip_Showalter_Hench.jpg\/180px-Philip_Showalter_Hench.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Philip_S._Hench","mini_bio":"<p><b>Philip Showalter Hench<\/b> (February 28, 1896 \u2013 March 30, 1965) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physician\" title=\"Physician\">physician<\/a>. Hench, along with his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mayo_Clinic\" title=\"Mayo Clinic\">Mayo Clinic<\/a> co-worker <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_Calvin_Kendall\" title=\"Edward Calvin Kendall\">Edward Calvin Kendall<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Swiss\" title=\"Swiss\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Swiss<\/a> chemist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Tadeus_Reichstein\" title=\"Tadeus Reichstein\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Tadeus Reichstein<\/a> was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1950 for the discovery of the hormone <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cortisone\" title=\"Cortisone\">cortisone<\/a>, and its application for the treatment of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rheumatoid_arthritis\" title=\"Rheumatoid arthritis\">rheumatoid arthritis<\/a>. The Nobel Committee bestowed the award for the trio's \"discoveries relating to the hormones of the adrenal cortex, their structure and biological effects.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-nobelsummary_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Philip_S._Hench#cite_note-nobelsummary-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Hench received his undergraduate education at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lafayette_College\" title=\"Lafayette College\">Lafayette College<\/a> in Easton, Pennsylvania, and received his medical training at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_Army_Medical_Corps\" title=\"United States Army Medical Corps\" class=\"mw-redirect\">United States Army Medical Corps<\/a> and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Pittsburgh\" title=\"University of Pittsburgh\">University of Pittsburgh<\/a>. He began working at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mayo_Clinic\" title=\"Mayo Clinic\">Mayo Clinic<\/a> in 1923, later serving as the head of the Department of Rheumatology. In addition to the Nobel Prize, Hench received many other awards and honors throughout his career. He also had a lifelong interest in the history and discovery of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Yellow_fever\" title=\"Yellow fever\">yellow fever<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Philip S. Hench","place_of_birth":"Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania ,  USA","place_of_death":null,"text":"Philip S. Hench , Physiology or Medicine, 1950","year":1950.0}